etymology.description: Depicts an upside-down newborn baby with inverted 子(子) (zǐ, "child") and three lower lines representing amniotic fluid or hair
etymology.interpretation: This character visually represents a newborn baby by showing an inverted depiction of 囗(圍) (wéi, "enclose") symbolizing being enclosed in amniotic fluid or the baby's hair, aligning with historical forms where 子(子) represented a child.
